vector<int> bfsTraversal(int n, vector<vector<int>> &adj)
{
    vector<int> bfs;
    vector<int> visited(n,0);
    queue<int> q;
    q.push(0);
    visited[0]=1;

    while(!q.empty())
    {
        int f = q.front();
        q.pop();
        bfs.push_back(f);
        for(auto it:adj[f])
        {
            if(!visited[it])
            {
                visited[it]=true;
                q.push(it);
            }
        }
    }
    return bfs;
}

Time and space:
Time Complexity: O(V + E)
✅ Why V (Vertices)?
Every node is visited exactly once
Because once visited → never pushed again

👉 So total node processing = O(V)

Why E (Edges)?
For every node, we iterate over its adjacency list:
for (auto it : adj[node])
Across the whole graph:
Every edge is explored once (directed)
Or twice (undirected: u→v and v→u)

Final Time Complexity
O(V) + O(E) = O(V + E)


Space Complexity: O(V)
visited array : Stores state for each node → O(V)

Quick Interview Summary 🚀
Time: O(V + E) → visit all nodes + edges
Space: O(V) → visited + queue + result

👉 Total edge work = O(E)
